  <section xml:id="ch-15-punctuation-sec-151">
    <title>The Purpose of Punctuation</title>

    <p>Punctuation marks are visual signals that clarify meaning and guide readers through text. They indicate pauses, separate elements, and show relationships between parts of sentences.</p>

    <p>Good punctuation makes prose easier to read and prevents misunderstanding:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><em>Let's eat grandma.</em> (disturbing)</p></li>
      <li><p><em>Let's eat, grandma.</em> (dinner invitation)</p></li>
    </ul>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="ch-15-punctuation-sec-152">
    <title>Terminal Punctuation</title>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Period (.)</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Ends declarative sentences and mild imperatives:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>The meeting is at noon.</p></li>
      <li><p>Please close the door.</p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Question Mark (?)</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Ends direct questions:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>What time is it?</p></li>
      <li><p>Have you finished?</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>Note</em>: Indirect questions take periods:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>She asked what time it was.</p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Exclamation Point (!)</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Indicates strong emotion or emphasis:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>Watch out!</p></li>
      <li><p>What a surprise!</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p>Use sparingly in formal writing.</p>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="ch-15-punctuation-sec-153">
    <title>The Comma</title>

    <p>The comma is the most frequently used—and misused—punctuation mark.</p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Comma in Compound Sentences</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Place a comma before a coordinating conjunction joining independent clauses:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>"The sun set, <em>and</em> the stars appeared."</p></li>
      <li><p>"She tried hard, <em>but</em> she didn't succeed."</p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Comma After Introductory Elements</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Use a comma after introductory phrases or clauses:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>After the meeting, we went to lunch.</p></li>
      <li><p>However, I disagree.</p></li>
      <li><p>Running quickly, she caught the bus.</p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Commas with Nonrestrictive Elements</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Set off nonrestrictive (non-essential) modifiers with commas:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>"My sister, <em>who lives in Boston</em>, is visiting."</p></li>
      <li><p>"The report, <em>which I submitted yesterday</em>, was approved."</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>Do not</em> use commas with restrictive (essential) modifiers:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><em>The students who studied passed.</em> (no commas—specifies which students)</p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Commas in Series</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Separate items in a list:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>She bought apples, oranges, and bananas.</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p>The comma before <em>and</em> (the Oxford comma) is optional but recommended for clarity:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><em>I admire my parents, Gandhi, and Mother Teresa.</em> (clear)</p></li>
      <li><p><em>I admire my parents, Gandhi and Mother Teresa.</em> (ambiguous)</p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Commas with Coordinate Adjectives</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Separate adjectives that independently modify the noun:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><em>a tall, elegant woman</em> (tall and elegant both modify woman)</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>Test</em>: If you can put <em>and</em> between them, use a comma.</p>

    <p><em>Don't</em> use commas between cumulative adjectives:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><em>a big red barn</em> (not ~~big, red barn~~—big red modifies barn together)</p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Comma Misuse</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p><em>Comma splice</em>: Using only a comma between independent clauses:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>~~The rain stopped, we went outside.~~</p></li>
      <li><p>Correct: <em>The rain stopped, and we went outside.</em></p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>Separating subject from verb</em>:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>~~The man who arrived late, was my cousin.~~</p></li>
      <li><p>Correct: <em>The man who arrived late was my cousin.</em></p></li>
    </ul>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="ch-15-punctuation-sec-154">
    <title>The Semicolon</title>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Between Independent Clauses</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Joins related independent clauses without a conjunction:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>The rain stopped; we went outside.</p></li>
      <li><p>She's talented; however, she lacks experience.</p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>In Complex Series</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Separates items in a series when items contain commas:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>The committee includes Dr. Smith, president; Mr. Jones, treasurer; and Ms. Lee, secretary.</p></li>
    </ul>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="ch-15-punctuation-sec-155">
    <title>The Colon</title>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Introducing Lists</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Use a colon after a complete sentence to introduce a list:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>Please bring the following items: a pen, a notebook, and a calculator.</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>Don't</em> use a colon after an incomplete sentence:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>~~Please bring: a pen, a notebook, and a calculator.~~</p></li>
      <li><p>Correct: <em>Please bring a pen, a notebook, and a calculator.</em></p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Introducing Explanations</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Use a colon to introduce an explanation or elaboration:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>She had one goal: to finish her degree.</p></li>
      <li><p>The answer was clear: we needed more data.</p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>In Formal Contexts</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Between titles and subtitles:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>Grammar Matters: A Guide to Standard English</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p>After salutations in formal letters:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>Dear Dr. Smith:</p></li>
    </ul>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="ch-15-punctuation-sec-156">
    <title>The Apostrophe</title>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Possession</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p><em>Singular nouns</em>: Add <em>'s</em></p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>the dog's tail</p></li>
      <li><p><em>James's book</em> (or James' book)</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p>*<em>Plural nouns ending in </em>-s**<em>: Add </em>'*</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>the dogs' tails</p></li>
      <li><p>the students' grades</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p>*<em>Plural nouns not ending in </em>-s**<em>: Add </em>'s*</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>the children's toys</p></li>
      <li><p>the women's team</p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Contractions</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Apostrophes replace omitted letters:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><em>don't</em> (do not)</p></li>
      <li><p><em>it's</em> (it is)</p></li>
      <li><p><em>they're</em> (they are)</p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Common Errors</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p><em>Its vs. It's</em>:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><em>Its</em> = possessive (The dog wagged its tail.)</p></li>
      <li><p><em>It's</em> = it is (It's raining.)</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>Their, There, They're</em>:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><em>Their</em> = possessive (Their house)</p></li>
      <li><p><em>There</em> = location (over there)</p></li>
      <li><p><em>They're</em> = they are (They're coming)</p></li>
    </ul>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="ch-15-punctuation-sec-157">
    <title>Dashes and Parentheses</title>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Em Dash (—)</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Sets off emphatic or interrupting material:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>The answer—surprisingly—was yes.</p></li>
      <li><p>She had one goal—and only one—to succeed.</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p>Creates stronger emphasis than commas.</p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>En Dash (–)</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Indicates ranges:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>pages 10–20</p></li>
      <li><p>the 2020–2021 academic year</p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Parentheses ( )</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Enclose supplementary or explanatory material:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>The results (see Table 3) were significant.</p></li>
      <li><p>She graduated in 2010 (the same year I started).</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p>Creates less emphasis than dashes.</p>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="ch-15-punctuation-sec-158">
    <title>Quotation Marks</title>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Direct Quotations</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Enclose exact words:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>She said, "I'll be there."</p></li>
      <li><p>"I'll be there," she said.</p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Titles</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Use for shorter works (articles, chapters, poems, songs):</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>I read "The Road Not Taken."</p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Punctuation with Quotation Marks</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p><em>American convention</em>: Periods and commas inside quotation marks:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>She said, "I agree."</p></li>
      <li><p>He called it "amazing," but I disagreed.</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>British convention</em>: Periods and commas may go outside if not part of the quotation.</p>

    <p>Question marks and exclamation points depend on the quotation:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><em>Did she say "yes"?</em> (question is mine)</p></li>
      <li><p><em>She asked, "Are you coming?"</em> (question is hers)</p></li>
    </ul>

  </section>

